<div id='panel'>
<h1>History of the Ecco community</h1>
<h2>
[ <a href='edit.pl?id=history-of-the-ecco-community'>Edit</a> ]
</h2>

<span id='tab'>I. The Undercaves</span>
<div id='panel'>
<h1>The Ultimate Ecco the Dolphin Website!</h1>

<div id='caption'>
<center>
<img src='../eccoserv/screenshots/undercaves-history.png'>
</center>
<br />
The Undercaves was the first Ecco the Dolphin fan website on the internet. 
</div>

<br />January 2000 to July 2001
<br />http://www.ecco-the-dolphin.org.nz/

<p>The Undercaves was the <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website that started it all. It began in January 2000 and was created by Jason Grindlay, who was known in the community as blackfin. This website was the first to feature both information about the games as well as an interactive community of users. </p>

<i>"The idea for The Undercaves began to form about a year ago, at that time I had just finally finished playing Ecco 2: The Tides of Time for the umpteenth time, since SEGA at that time didn't seem to be inclined to continue the series and I wanted more, I started searching for Ecco websites on the net but quickly found that... there weren't any! I was also hooked on Sonic the Hedgehog at that time, I remember spending many hours browsing the many Sonic websites. I wanted the sort of the experience I had got on the Sonic websites but in terms of Ecco, but I couldn't because I couldn't find any other fans.</i>

<p><i>At that time I had been teaching myself HTML for the last year or so but I hadn't found anything to make a website about yet, needless to say the solution to both my problems was obvious, I would make an Ecco website!" – Jason Grindlay</i></p>

The site featured a modified version of Ultimate Bulletin Board that allowed users to post questions and information to share with others. There was also a java applet that linked users to an IRC chat room that allowed them interact with one another.

<p>The best part of the site was the fan stuff section where users could submit artwork, stories and games based on <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i>. There was a word search that if solved would give the URL to the secret page.</p>

Arkonviox.com spawned from The Undercaves and became its biggest competitor for a user base. The competition became known as the infamous website wars of who could grow the biggest site and find the most interesting content. The Undercaves eventually ran dry of users as Arkonviox.com grew in popularity. Jason eventually threw in the towel and passed ownership over to Johnny de Alba, owner of Arkonviox.com. The site was officially closed August 2001 and its content was merged with the old Arkonviox.com.

