<br /><br />
<span id='tab'> II. Arkonviox.com</span>
<div id='panel'>
<h1>The Ecco the Dolphin Website to end all Ecco the Dolphin Websites!</h1>

<div id='caption'>
<center>
<img src='../eccoserv/captions/arkonvioxx200.jpg'>
</center>
<br />
Arkonviox.com had the best <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> fan artwork on the Internet. 
</div>

<br />November 2000 to August 2004
<br />http://www.arkonviox.com/</p>

Arkonviox.com started off as a Geocities free site called The City of Tantalus that featured concept art for the game <i>A Stone in Time</i>. It eventually grew into an </i>Ecco the Dolphin website</i> featuring fan artwork and fan stories in November 2000. 

<p>It became very popular with Undercave’s users who where able to request Arkonviox.com co-owner Mario de Alba to design forum avatars for them. The avatars were hosted on Arkonviox.com and a URL was given to the user who could use the image links on The Undercaves.</p>

The key to making Arkonviox.com popular was its devotion to fan-related material. It became very popular among <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> artists and spawned the most beautiful <i>Ecco</i> fanart ever seen.

<p>The blundercaves web comic was a big hit amongst Undercave’s users for its exaggerated comical depiction of The Undercaves community. It featured Undercaves owner blackfin as clumsy fool filled with empty threats.</p>

What made Arkonviox.com unique from other websites was enigma, a content manager that allowed the site to alter its appearance through the use of skins. The site had a total of eight skins, all based on level themes from the actual games.

<p>When Arkonviox.com owner Johnny de Alba acquired the Undercaves website, enigma was scrapped for a more traditional design. The site dropped what made it unique in order to merge content from the Undercaves. Postnuke eventually replaced enigma as a content manager, but it wasn’t the same. It gave the site a more generic look and made adding skins challenging.</p>

Arkonviox.com came to an end in November 2004 when its decline in updates lead to the decline of community activity. With Arkonviox.com gone the era of <i>Ecco</i> websites that strove to be better then one another came to an end.

<br /><br />
