<br /><br />
<span id='tab'>III. Caverns of Hope</span>
<div id='panel'>
<h1>Ecco the Dolphin: Caverns of Hope</h1>

<div id='caption'>
<center>
<img src='../eccoserv/captions/caverns-of-hopex200.jpg'>
</center>
<br />
Caverns of Hope is the oldest <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website still in existence.
</div>

<br />September 2001 to Current
<br />http://www.cavernsofhope.com/</p>

Caverns of Hope was created in September 2001 by Hauke and GTK. At the time The Undercaves had officially closed, making Arkonviox.com the only <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website on the Internet. Hauke was not satisfied with Arkonviox.com being the source of the Ecco Community. He and GTK were former Undercaves members and felt that they should start a new Ecco website. 

<p>Before The Undercaves closed, no one thought to challenge it by creating another <i>Ecco</i> website. The Undercaves was understood by everyone to be the best, a monument to our hero, Ecco. No other was needed until Arkonviox.com challenged this. With the Undercaves gone the unspoken rule no longer applied and a new website was opened: Caverns of Hope.</p>

Arkonviox.com would finally met its match, an <i>Ecco</i> website that would ignore history and its roots to create a new community. The site was created in secret, started out small and grew to become a big <i>Ecco</i> website. A website war developed between Arkonviox.com and Caverns of Hope over members but eventually an alliance was formed that would last until Arkonviox.com ended. 

<p>When Arkonviox.com closed, Caverns of Hope reached a new peak in popularity. The site grew in activity with members writing stories, doing artwork, even combining in a joint effort to create a fan game. The site grew out of control for the moderators, as it became the biggest thing to hit children since Mr. Rogers. The conflict of Caverns of Hope becoming a good website or a cesspool went unnoticed by its members but well noticed by its owners.</p>

Balance in the form of a cheap, well-known forum hack lead to the site's end. The forum's deletion crippled the site and the admins pulled the plug on all interactive parts leading to the death of the <i>Ecco</i> community. 

<p>Today Caverns of Hope is a resource site for <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i>. It has a guest book where users comment and occasionally ask questions about the site. If you're lucky, you may even get a response from one of the administrators.</p>
</div>

<br /><br />
<span id='tab'>IV. The Atlantis</span>
<div id='panel'>
<h1>Ecco the Dolphin - The Atlantis</h1>

<div id='caption'>
<center>
<img src='../eccoserv/captions/the-atlantisx200.jpg'>
</center>
<br />
The Atlantis is a very successful Russian-language <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website.
</div>

<br />August 2006 - Current
<br />http://www.mod-atlantis.net/

<p>The Atlantis was created in August 2006 by Moduvator, who was a former member of Caverns of Hope and Arkonviox.com. Arkonviox.com at the time was a no-rules tyranny where any forum member could be banned for whatever reason. Unhappy with his treatment on Arkonviox.com, Moduvator joined Caverns of Hope's forum for a more pleasant atmosphere.</p>

Moduvator eventually gained the administrators' respect, becoming a moderator of the site's forum. Because of his experience with Arkonviox.com, Moduvator's goal was to create a censored forum everyone could enjoy. He had a vision of what Caverns of Hope's community could be that didn't agree with the site's owners.

<p><i>Despite the difficulties I've had with him I still want to mention him for helping out by watching the forum in a time of crisis where we were under quite some attacks. - Hauke</i></p>

Moduvator eventually quit his membership with Caverns of Hope and formed a new website called The Atlantis. Because of the Russian pronunciation of words with a definitive title, it's called The Atlantis rather than Atlantis, signifying Moduvator's heritage. 

<p>The Atlantis began as an English language <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website but changed pace a few years later to become a Russian-only website. Today The Atlantis is a very successful <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website with a flourishing community.</p>
</div>

<br /><br />
<span id='tab'>V. DARK SEA</span>
<div id='panel'>
<h1>The Ultimate Ecco Resource</h1>

<div id='caption'>
<center>
<img src='../eccoserv/captions/darkseax200.jpg'>
</center>
<br />
DARK SEA's goal is to be a resource for everything related to <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i>.
</div>

<br />November 2000 - Current
<br />http://ecco-darksea.com/

<p>It is hard to place a date when DARK SEA began since it derived from Histronic's ExtremeEcco, Ecco 2 Beta Website. It began as the first website to document the <i>Ecco 2 Beta</i>, mistakenly called a beta by the original dumpers. The website aimed to be an in-your-face documentation of the <i>Ecco 2 Beta</i>, inspired by the Undercaves and Arkonviox.com.</p>

Epicenter eventually took over operations and rebuilt the <i>Ecco 2</i> Beta website with a more detailed article that took documentation deeper. When Arkonviox.com closed and Caverns of Hope ceased operations, Epicenter's <i>Ecco 2 Beta</i> website became DARK SEA. The goal of DARK SEA became to document everything related to <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i>. Although it does not as a general rule contain <i>Ecco: Defender of the Future</i> content, it does have music by Tim Follin from <i>Defender</i>.

<p>DARK SEA is the only <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website to have ever contacted most of the original developers for <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i>. It is also the only <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website to host many prototype versions of <i>Ecco 2: The Tides of Time</i>. Much of the old content from Arkonviox.com has been merged into DARK SEA, but because of how large the site is, Arkonviox.com only makes up a mere fraction of the content.</p>
</div>

<br /><br />
<span id='tab'>R.I.P.</span>

<div id='panel'>
Isles of Tranquility - A fan website created by Orion and Flippy to take on the community of Caverns of Hope when the site's forum closed. Flippy was developing an <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> fan game that was 3D. Because of Orion's lack of interest and Flippy's lack of time the site closed not too long after it opened.

<p>Eccocide - This website opened a little after the Undercaves opened and was an attempt at another <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> fan website. It was inspired by the Undercaves but never managed to make it past a one-page site. It is only mentioned here because it was the first attempt after the Undercaves to create an <i>Ecco</i> website, since back then no one else bothered to challenge the Undercaves' dominance.</p>

<a href='http://ecco-le-dauphin.ifrance.com/' target='_blank'>Ecco le Dolphin</a> - This is the weirdest of <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> websites because it's hard to say if it's dead or alive! The site is updated once every few years with a new look and has a little bit of content. It is a very old French <i>Ecco the Dolphin</i> website.

<p>EccoWorld - This was an MSN Communities website that inspired Arkonviox.com the most because of it revealed web design's ease of creation. Had this site not existed, Arkonviox.com would have never happened, and all because of this one-page <i>Ecco</i> website created by Ecco the Barbarian, Internet hero of the time.</p>
</div>
</div>

